data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>`, which lets you also inspect the exception:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));

    // Optional: verify the parameter name
    Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName);
}
```

**Why:**
- `[ExpectedException]` is obsolete — it can't verify exception properties and passes even if the *wrong line* throws
- `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` matches only the exact type (use `Assert.Throws<T>` if derived types should also match)
- The returned exception object lets you assert on `Message`, `ParamName`, `InnerException`, etc.
